body:
If you import tensorflow and start a session like that without closing it, the GPU cannot be allowed in DLC. Don't import tensorflow and start a session, and then you can run. DLC. Typically, when you have a new installation, you should run a test script to see if it's working. 

Follow here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IOWtKn3l33s

Hi, thanks for your response. When I run DLC on my project without importing tensorflow first, it still doesn't use the GPU. When I follow the YouTube video linked above I get the code below. Any more help would be greatly appreciated!

This means you have a mismatch in the cuDNN, CUDA and tensorflow version. I don't use Windows for GPU tasks, but be sure you have a cuDNN that is installed that works with CUDA 10, such as 7.4; otherwise, this is just the GPU installation, and hard if not impossible for me to troubleshoot: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50622525/which-tensorflow-and-cuda-version-combinations-are-compatible

Hi @hsolb it seems you only have 1 graphic card in the computer, i.e, typically it's best to have 2, one that comes standard with any computer shipped, then you add in another graphics card for deep learning applications into another PCI slot on the computer. Also, if you are just using it for DLC, I highly highly highly recommend ubuntu! 20.04 already has cuda installed, there is nothing to do. It's faster for DLC, and I find way easier to use. Plus, you can use Docker. 

I don't have a lot of GPU resrouces complied, but for DLC: http://DLCcourse.deeplabcut.org hope that helps!
